subsubsection.p:
Then let D be the difference in total point values initially awarded to the two players. Before the sharing of the legion, the score is Caesar 80 and Cleopatra 40 for a difference of 80-40=40, so D = 40. The rule for equitable division is that the quantity
x=\frac{D}{S}
is the fraction of the shared item that is given away to the other player. In the example, we get x = 40=90 = 4=9 = 0.444. Thus, Caesar needs to give 0.444 (or 44.4%) of the legion to Cleopatra and keep 5/9=0.556 (or 55.6%) of it for himself. The share of 0.444 is worth 0.444\cdot 40=17.8 to Cleopatra, while the share of 0.556 is worth 0.556\cdot 50=27.8 to Caesar. Both players end up with a total of 57.8. These results are summarized in the table below.
